International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 4 Feb 2014
Source: FreshPlaza, ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) report [edited]
http://www.freshplaza.com/article/117604/Cherry-disease-outbreak-suspected-in-Tasmania


Cherry disease outbreak suspected in Tasmania
---------------------------------------------
The Tasmanian Department of Primary Industries, Parks, Water and Environment [DPIPWE] is investigating a suspected case of little cherry disease on a property in the state's south. The disease has never before been detected in Australia.

Andrew Bishop, DPIPWE, says that at this stage, there is no knowledge how the disease came to be in Tasmania, but his department is investigating. "We're doing what we call a trace-back investigation to determine the origin of the plant material. The disease takes some years to manifest itself in the tree, so it's been within the identified trees for some years. We will have to look back at where that planting material came from, and it may be that we have actually found it in Tasmania but it may be elsewhere in Australia."

DNA testing of leaf samples from the tree suspected to be infected are being undertaken and results are expected later this week.

Mr Bishop says the disease is spread in overseas countries by an insect called the apple mealybug, which is not present in Australia. He says if the case is confirmed any infected trees will be removed, but the orchard in question is not under threat. DPIPWE is calling for calm among Tasmanian cherry growers.

