communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Little cherry disease (LCD) is a serious problem for sweet and sour cherry producers in parts of northern Europe and North America. It can be caused by 2 closteroviruses, _Little cherry virus 1_ (LChV-1, not yet assigned to a genus) and LChV-2 (genus _Ampelovirus_), in single or mixed infections.

Symptoms vary with host cultivars, but may include reduced size and quality of fruit, premature leaf reddening, stunting of seedlings, and some loss of tree vigour. All commercial cherry cultivars are susceptible, and ornamental flowering cherries can be asymptomatic reservoirs of LChV-1.

LChV-2 is transmitted by one or several species of mealybug vectors which can be spread by wind and with packing material in their nymph stages. An insect vector for LChV-1 is not known. Both viruses can be spread by both shoot and root grafting and with infected plant material. Disease management for LCD includes use of certified clean planting stock and budwood, elimination of inoculum (removal of infected trees, as mentioned above), and vector control for LChV-2.

While the report above states the absence of the apple mealybug (_Phenacoccus aceris_) as a vector for LChV-2 in Australia, it has been suggested that virus spread by other mealybug species cannot be excluded. It remains to be confirmed which of the 2 viruses the suspected outbreak is due to, but if no insect vectors are involved in Tasmania, the disease will be easier to control by phytosanitation and increased standards of quarantine certification for _Prunus_ planting material.

